14 WHEREAS, Girl Scouts offers hands-on, girl-led, and girl-centered learning in STEM, the
15 outdoors, and entrepreneurship and provides abundant opportunities to help girls develop
16 invaluable life skills; and
17 WHEREAS, the Girl Scout Gold Award, the highest honor a Girl Scout can earn,
18 acknowledges each recipient's power and dedication to not only bettering herself but also to
19 making the world a better place for others; and
20 WHEREAS, more than 59 million American women are Girl Scout alumnae, and 2.6 million
21 girls and adult volunteers are active members; and
22 WHEREAS, the movement started by Juliette Gordon Low now reaches every corner of the
23 world with Girl Scouts living throughout the United States, its territories, and in more than
24 90 countries across the globe; and
25 WHEREAS, today, the Girl Scouts of Historic Georgia and Greater Atlanta Councils serve
26 approximately 43,000 Girl Scout members in the State of Georgia.
27 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES that
28 the members of this body recognize February 4, 2025, as Girl Scout Day at the state capitol
29 and commend the Girl Scouts as a national leader in developing girls of courage, confidence,
30 and character.
31 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the Clerk of the House of Representatives is authorized
32 and directed to make appropriate copies of this resolution available for distribution to the
33 public and the press.
